Introduction

This project investigates how average team points and assists have changed in the NBA from 2010 to 2024, and which teams rank among the top five in each category over this period. By analyzing season-level team totals, I aim to uncover long-term offensive trends and highlight standout teams that exemplify scoring efficiency and ball movement. These metrics offer insight into evolving league strategies, including the rise of pace-and-space offenses and position-less play.

Data Preparation

The dataset used for this analysis includes regular season totals for NBA teams from 2010 to 2024. It was provided as a CSV file containing variables such as âteamâ, âseason_yearâ, âpts (total points)â, and âast (total assists)â. The data was cleaned using the janitor package to standardize column names, and exploratory summaries were generated using dplyr and ggplot2.

Key preparation steps included renaming and cleaning column headers, grouping data by season_year to calculate league-wide averages, and aggregating by team to identify top performers in scoring and assists. No missing values were found in the key variables used for analysis.

Exploratory Analysis

The dataset contains 15 seasons of NBA team-level data, with each row representing a teamâs total performance for a given season. The primary variables analyzed were:

  • pts: total points scored by the team in a season

  • ast: total assists recorded by the team in a season

  • season_year: formatted as âYYYYâYYâ to represent each NBA season

Distribution of key variables:

  • Average team points ranged from ~96 in 2011â12 to over 114 in 2023â24

  • Average team assists increased from ~21 in 2010â11 to nearly 27 in 2023â24

These distributions suggest a steady upward trend in offensive output and playmaking across the league.

# Group by season and calculate averages across teams
nba_summary <- nba |> 
  group_by(season_year) |> 
  summarize(
    avg_pts = mean(pts, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_ast = mean(ast, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )
nba_summary <- nba_summary |> 
  mutate(season_numeric = as.numeric(str_sub(season_year, 1, 4)))
ggplot(nba_summary, aes(x = season_numeric, y = avg_pts)) +
  geom_line(color = "darkred", size = 1.2) +
  labs(title = "Average Team Points per Season (2010â2024)",
       x = "Season", y = "Points") +
  theme_minimal()

top_pts_teams <- nba |> 
  group_by(team_name) |> 
  summarize(
    avg_pts = mean(pts, na.rm = TRUE)

Preliminary Results

Two line graphs were generated to visualize changes in average team points and assists over time. The scoring graph displays a consistent increase, with spikes around 2015â16 and 2018â19. The assist graph reveals a similar upward trajectory, peaking in 2023â24.

These trends reflect broader strategic shifts in the NBA, including increased pace, three-point shooting, and emphasis on ball movement.

Additionally, the top 5 teams by average points and average assists consistently demonstrated offensive excellence, either through high scoring or strong ball distribution. The Golden State Warriors notably appear in both lists, showing their dominance in both scoring and play-making.Â 

Conclusion

From 2010 to 2024, NBA teams have shown a clear upward trend in both scoring and assists, reflecting the leagueâs evolution toward faster, more collaborative offensive systems. The top-performing teams in each category highlight the strategic diversity across franchises, with some excelling in raw scoring and others in ball movement. These findings support the narrative that modern NBA offenses prioritize efficiency, spacing, and teamwork; thus showing a shift that continues to shape the gameâs future.
